 1. Pick a T1 testbed

  In ansible/testbed.yaml, find a 7260 entry with topo: t1-* (e.g. t1-lag or t1-64-lag). Note the
  testbed name and DUT hostname.

  2. SSH to the DUT and pick one port

  Pick any single front-panel port (e.g. Ethernet0). Capture its current state for rollback:
  show interfaces autoneg status Ethernet0
  show interfaces status Ethernet0

  3. Enable AN on that one port

  On the DUT (matches what tests/platform_tests/test_auto_negotiation.py:203 does):
  sudo config interface autoneg Ethernet0 enabled
  sudo config interface advertised-speeds Ethernet0 all
  sudo config save -y
  Then verify:
  show interfaces autoneg status Ethernet0
  show interfaces status Ethernet0    # should be "up", speed negotiated

  4. Manual warmboot

  On the DUT (matches tests/common/reboot.py:85):
  sudo warm-reboot
  Expected: ~300s reboot window, ~90s stabilization, finalizer up to 180s. Don't interrupt.

  5. Post-warmboot verification

  After SSH is back:
  show warm_restart state            # all components should be "reconciled"
  show interfaces autoneg status Ethernet0
  show interfaces status Ethernet0   # link still up, AN still enabled, speed preserved
  Also sanity-check that the rest of the box came back clean:
  show interfaces status | grep -i down
  show ip bgp summary                 # BGP sessions re-established

  6. Rollback

  sudo config interface autoneg Ethernet0 disabled
  sudo config interface speed Ethernet0 <original-speed>
  sudo config save -y

  What you're actually proving

  - AN config survives a warmboot (persists in config_db post-reload).
  - The link renegotiates / stays up across the warmboot data-plane preservation window.
  - No traffic blackhole on that port during the warmboot finalizer.

  One note on existing coverage

  test_verify_portspeed_configuration_across_reboot (lines 374-408) does port-speed-across-reload, but
  it's gated to platform x86_64-8101_32fh_o-r0 and uses config_reload, not warm-reboot. So your manual
  test isn't redundant — it's actually covering a gap.

  Want me to also draft a quick traffic-check step (e.g. ping/iperf across that port during the
  warmboot) before you run it?
